<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also my initial assumption was that, if Musk w=
as selling Twitter shares, he was selling=C2=A0<em>his=C2=A0</em>shares: In=
 his acquisition of Twitter, he committed to buy all of the shares for $54.=
20, but he reserved the right to syndicate some of that commitment, and a n=
umber of other investors ended up putting in money or rolling over their sh=
ares into Musk=E2=80=99s private Twitter. Up until the deal=E2=80=99s closi=
ng, he was apparently in conversations about selling more of his shares, an=
d there=E2=80=99s no reason he couldn=E2=80=99t keep doing that after closi=
ng.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the FT article indicates that the proposed=
