solid; background-color: #ccc;">  I speculated a little bit</a> about why F=
TX and Alameda =E2=80=94=C2=A0which over the summer were running into fatal=
 trouble themselves =E2=80=94=C2=A0might have devoted so much of their scar=
ce money to bailing out other insolvent crypto shadow banks. I hope that th=
e explanation above helps make the answer clear? One of my proposed explana=
tions last month was:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Crypto prices, and firms, crashed =
earlier this year, and FTX/Alameda spotted an=C2=A0<em>opportunity to acqui=
re new customer deposits cheaply and use them for nefarious purposes</em>. =
Like, you pay zero dollars for the equity of some busted crypto lending pla=
tform, you roll the customers over to become FTX customers, you cash out an=
yone who wants to cash out, you assume that most people will trust FTX (the=
ir savior) and=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>cash out, and then you use=C2=A0<em>t=
heir=C2=A0</em>deposits to fund your wild speculations. If FTX/Alameda were=
=C2=A0<em>already=C2=A0</em>using customer deposits for bad reasons, and lo=
sing them, then acquiring more customer deposits would be a way to keep thi=
ngs going.</p></blockquote>
